This paper is likely to belong to the category of Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) as it deals with information extraction, which is a subfield of natural language processing. Additionally, the paper proposes a novel tagging scheme, which is a common technique used in NLP. The paper also mentions the use of end-to-end models, which are often used in deep learning-based NLP tasks. 

The paper could also belong to the category of Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) as it deals with machine learning-based approaches to extract entities and relations. 

The category of Machine Learning (cs.LG) is also a likely fit as the paper discusses different end-to-end models for the joint extraction task. 

Information Retrieval (cs.IR) is another possible category as the paper deals with extracting information from text data. 

Finally, Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) is a possible category as the paper mentions the use of neural networks in the proposed end-to-end model.
